🔹 Producer
A producer is a component that creates data or events.
It sends something.
🔹 Consumer
A consumer is a component that receives and processes data or events.
It reads something.

✅ Simple real‑life analogy
📦 Amazon order system
You place an order → Producer
Order queue → buffer
Warehouse system processes order → Consumer
Producer does not care when or how the consumer processes it.


✅ Producers & Consumers in Software Systems
1️⃣ Messaging / Event Systems (Most common)
Example: Azure Service Bus / Kafka / Event Hub
[Producer] → [Queue / Topic] → [Consumer]

Producer:
App sending messages
API publishing events

Consumer:
Worker service
Background job
Analytics processor

✅ Decoupled
✅ Scalable
✅ Fault‑tolerant

2️⃣ Database Context (Important for You)
Producer
Application writing to DB
INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE

Consumer
Application reading from DB
SELECT queries
Reports
Downstream services

Example:
Checkout service writes order → Producer
Billing service reads order → Consumer


3️⃣ API Context
Producer
Client calling an API
Mobile app / frontend / external tenant

Consumer
Backend service handling the request

Example:
Tenant A floods API → Producer misbehaves
Backend + DB → Consumers get overloaded

This is where throttling and isolation matter.
✅ Why Producers & Consumers Matter (Operationally)
Key problem
Producers can generate work faster than consumers can handle.

If unchecked:
Queues grow
DB saturates
Latency spikes
Errors occur
✅ This is the root cause of most outages

✅ Where Throttling Fits (Connect the dots)
Component            Role           Protection 
API client          Producer        Rate limiting
App service         Producer        Concurrency limits
Message queue       Buffer          Backpressure 
DB                  Consumer        Connection limits
💡 You throttle producers to protect consumers
Never the other way around.



